# C# Coding Standards for GoalifyNow

## Language Features & Syntax

### Primary Constructors (MANDATORY)
**Always use primary constructors for classes with dependencies:**

```csharp
// GOOD - Primary constructor (cleaner, preferred)
public class UserService(
    AuthDbContext db, 
    ICurrentContextService context,
    IPasswordHasher passwordHasher,
    ILogger<UserService> logger)
{
    public async Task<Result<User>> GetUserAsync(Guid id)
    {
        return await db.Users.FindAsync(id);
    }
}

// BAD - Traditional constructor (avoid)
public class UserService
{
    private readonly AuthDbContext _db;
    private readonly ICurrentContextService _context;
    
    public UserService(AuthDbContext db, ICurrentContextService context)
    {
        _db = db;
        _context = context;
    }
}
```

### Records for DTOs and Events
```csharp
// Use records for immutable DTOs
public record RegisterRequestDto
{
    public string Email { get; init; } = string.Empty;
    public string Password { get; init; } = string.Empty;
    public string FirstName { get; init; } = string.Empty;
    public string LastName { get; init; } = string.Empty;
}

// Use records for domain events
public record UserRegisteredEvent : IDomainEvent
{
    public Guid EventId { get; init; } = Guid.NewGuid();
    public DateTime OccurredOn { get; init; } = DateTime.UtcNow;
    public Guid UserId { get; init; }
    public string Email { get; init; } = string.Empty;
}
```

### var vs Explicit Types
```csharp
// Use var when type is obvious
var user = new User();
var users = await db.Users.ToListAsync();
var result = CreateUser(dto);

// Use explicit type when not obvious
IEnumerable<User> GetActiveUsers() => ...;
User? FindUser(Guid id) => ...;
```

### Expression-Bodied Members
```csharp
// Use => for simple members
public string FullName => $"{FirstName} {LastName}";
public bool IsValid => Email is not null && Email.Contains("@");

// Single-statement methods
public User GetUser(Guid id) => db.Users.Find(id);

// Single-statement properties with get
public decimal TotalAmount => Items.Sum(i => i.Amount);
```

