## Async/Await Patterns

### Always Async for I/O
```csharp
// GOOD - Async for database operations
public async Task<User?> GetUserAsync(Guid id, CancellationToken ct = default)
{
    return await db.Users.FindAsync(id, ct);
}

// BAD - Sync for database operations
public User? GetUser(Guid id)
{
    return db.Users.Find(id);  // Blocking call
}
```

### CancellationToken Parameter
```csharp
// Include CancellationToken with default value
public async Task<Result<User>> RegisterAsync(
    RegisterRequestDto dto, 
    CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
{
    var user = User.Create(dto.Email);
    db.Users.Add(user);
    await db.SaveChangesAsync(cancellationToken);
    return Result<User>.Success(user);
}
```

### ConfigureAwait
```csharp
// In library code, use ConfigureAwait(false)
public async Task<string> GetDataAsync()
{
    var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url).ConfigureAwait(false);
    return response;
}

// In application code (ASP.NET Core), ConfigureAwait not needed
public async Task<IActionResult> GetUser(Guid id)
{
    var user = await userService.GetUserAsync(id);
    return Ok(user);
}
```

